Manuscript: Edinburgh EUL La. iii.21

This manuscript contains a number of calendars, with annotations, several medical treatises, and a tract on astrology, including the astrology of medicine. The manuscript concludes with some medical notes in later hands, in Scots, Latin, and Gaelic. Among these are the noted Beaton genealogies. The manuscript was produced in Ireland by Cairbre Ó Ceanmháin for John Beaton of Ballinabe in about 1563; John Beaton may have been present during the manuscript's production. Notes are added throughout the manuscript by several later members of the Beaton family.

Hands

Contents

Summary

The astrological tract that concludes the manuscript contains an account of the movements of the sun, moon, planets, and constellations; the etymologies of their names; the parts of the body they govern; and the changes in the earth's seasons that coincide with changes in the heavens.

Text Summary
Filiation of Text

The tract quotes Albamasar (Abu Maʿshar) and Isidore [of Seville?], and possibly a treatise on the Astrolabe. No other versions of this Gaelic text are known at this time.

Notes

1. "Astrolabe"; this could refer to the scientific instrument or to one of several treatises composed upon it.

2. When fol. 105va begins, the text is discussing Libra, having apparently omitted details on the planetary conjunctions of Virgo. This seems to be a textual lacuna, as there is no sign of physical loss from any of the (admittedly late) foliations and Libra immediately follows Virgo, so it is not clear what an entire missing folio, if that be the cause, would have contained in order to span the gap.

3. A suspension stroke was inscribed above the tironian et that concludes "soiget" but it appears to have been partially scrubbed out; it is not clear what it was meant to stand for.

4. Abyssinia?

5. Burgundy?

6. What is "buried" in the constellations, and why this should explain them being called "changeable", is not clear. Perhaps this verb is instead a form of con-imchloí ("changes").
